ng, J. (2013); WHO, Department of Reproductive Health and Research, London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, South African Medical Research Council (2013). Global and regional estimates of violence against women \u2013 Prevalence and health effects of intimate partner violence and non-partner sexual violence. 8 Ibid. 9 Ibid 10 Ibid 11 Ibid 12 Jewkes, R., Dunkle K., Nduna M. & Shai N. (2010). Intimate partner violence, relationship gender power inequity, and incidence of HIV infection in young women in South Africa: a cohort study. The Lancet 367, 41\u201348. 20 depression, substance abuse, suicidality and anxiety.13 In too many cases, VAWG ends in murder.14 Children living in homes where violence against women occurs are more likely to be abused themselves.15 Children who experienced physical or sexual abuse have a greater likelihood of suffering depression, suicidality, post-traumatic stress disorder, unwanted pregnancy, alcohol dependency and sexually transmitted infections.16 Boys who witness violence against women in their homes are at risk of perpetrating such violence later in life, whereas girls in similar situations are more likely to become victims of violence in later life.17 Further, childhood abuse and neglect increases the risk of developing anti-social and violent behaviour which, for boys, may include rape perpetration.18 These consequences affect not only the individual survivors and victims, but also their children and families as well as impacting on public health costs and potential lost productivity. Therefore, the fundamental human rights violation of violence against women and girls needs to be addressed urgently. RISK FACTORS FOR VIOLENCE AGAINST WOMEN AND GIRLS The UN interagency Framework to Underpin Action to Prevent VAWG19 details an extensive list of risk factors for VAWG victimization and perpetration, categorized within a nested social ecological 13 Ibid.; Abrahams N., Jewkes R. & Mathews, S. (2013). Depressive symptomatology after a sexual assault: Understanding victim- perpetrator relationships and the role of social perceptions. African Journal of Psychiatry. Filipas, H. & Ullman S. E. (2006. Child sexual abuse, coping responses, self-blame, posttraumatic stress disorder, and adult sexual revictimization. Journal of Interpersonal Violence, 21, 652\u2013672. Kilpatrick, D.G., Acierno, R., Resnick, H.S., Saunders, B.E. & Best, C.L. (1997). A 2-year longitudinal analysis of the relationships between violent assault and substance abuse in women. Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology, 65, 834\u2013847. Myer, L., Smit, J., Roux, L. L., Parker, S., Stein, D. J. & Seedat, S. (2008.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b08f245f-f2d4-4c43-a64f-091120e40b84": {"__data__": {"id_": "b08f245f-f2d4-4c43-a64f-091120e40b84", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/promising-strides-toward-ending-violence-against-women-and-girls-asia-and-pacific-region", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Promising strides toward ending violence against women and girls in the Asia and the Pacific Region", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/promising-strides-toward-ending-violence-against-women-and-girls-asia-and-pacific-region", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "10a2c52693654acda975b8b570993f5dbde07aeff229d26958b663de0ceded66"}, "2": {"node_id": "f80c275a-a487-49a6-a1f6-d2c75635f449", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/p